{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"061f1470-0292-4cd1-94ab-191ce8b57930","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet-sdk` isn't in the container, use `dotnet-trace` as a [global tool via the .NET install script](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace).\n- For **production-safe** collection without the SDK, consider using **`dotnet monitor`** as a sidecar — it exposes an HTTP API to collect traces on-demand without exec'ing in.\n- Copy the trace out with `kubectl cp <pod>:/path/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0baf44aa-a725-476a-a557-68f32e7e71ed","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I should provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"2182:32BB22:623140:72465D:69F00D12"},"id":"9c4efaa6-e483-44c4-a5b7-3c0dae944cc3","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:27:59.242Z","parentId":"b5a88339-ede4-4b7c-9889-ba0f5aee1545"}
